From David Ward Subject Re Command Loss Timer Re Galileo Update In article Jim Cobban Having read in the past about the fail safe mechanisms on spacecraft I had assumed that the Command Loss Timer had that sort of However I always find disturbing the oxymoron of a NO OP command that does If the command changes the behavior or status of the spacecraft it is not a NO OP I know its semantics but the no op doesn't do The Command Loss Timer is simply looking for a command any A no op is simply a spacecraft command that drops bits into the big bit bucket in the No op also get used as timekeepers to provide millisecond delays between command sequences used on the thruster preps on GRO er Compton and to verify command links at the beginning of TDRS All in all a rather useful And an intelligent FDC test on Galileo the Command Loss Timer David GSFC still looking for GRO data even though I'm the wrong David